Lab 2b

Data Visualization

Statistical programming with R

For this practical, you will need to load the packages ggplot2, dplyr, and patchwork. If displaying multiple plot in one figure, use the R chunk options fig.width (default = 7), fig.height (default = 5) and/or fig.asp (height:width ratio) to display the plots in a nice format. To avoid messages by ggplot() being printed to the html, set the global chunk option to message = FALSE

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(patchwork)
knitr::opts_chunk$set(message = FALSE)

For a quick reference of ggplot2 functions, consult

  • ggplot2 Cheatsheet

  • ggplot2 Reference

The diamonds data

The dataset for this practical is the diamonds dataset from the package ggplot2.

  1. Check the help page of this tibble for its content, and display the first 10 rows of the data in your HTML.
diamonds

The diamonds data set has more than 50.000 rows, which is a lot. To simplify matters, we will work with a random sample of 500 cases.

  1. Set the seed to 100, and randomly sample 500 cases from the dataset diamonds using the slice_sample() function. Save the resulting data set as my_diamonds.
set.seed(100)
my_diamonds <- slice_sample(diamonds, n = 500)

One variable

In the following exercises we display plots numeric and of categorical/discrete variables. Check the geoms overview in the lecture sheets for the different options.

  1. In a 1 x 3 plot array, plot the distribution of variable carat using the three different geoms. Add a title with the name of the appropriate geom to each plot. The chunk option fig.asp = .35 displays the plots in a nice format.
p <- ggplot(my_diamonds, aes(x = carat))

p + geom_histogram(bins = ) + 
    ggtitle("histogram") +

p + geom_density() + 
    ggtitle("density plot") +
  
p + geom_boxplot() + 
    ggtitle("box plot")

Discrete variables are variables with countable values (i.e. categorical variables or variables with a small number of integer values). The most common option for such variables is the bar plot

  1. Display the bar plots of the factors cut, color and clarity in a 1 x 3 plot array. Make sure that the labels of the categories are readable (i.e., not overlapping).
  ggplot(my_diamonds, aes(y = cut)) + 
    geom_bar() +
  
  ggplot(my_diamonds, aes(y = color)) + 
    geom_bar() +
  
  ggplot(my_diamonds, aes(y = clarity)) + 
    geom_bar()

Two variables

The combinations between numeric and categorical/discrete variables requires different geoms. Check the cheat sheet again for the appropriate options.

  1. In the first row of one figure, display a box and violin plot of the variables price and cut, an in the second row a density plot. Use the / symbol to start a new row.
(ggplot(my_diamonds, aes(price, cut)) + 
    geom_boxplot() +
  
ggplot(my_diamonds, aes(price, cut)) + 
    geom_violin() ) /
  
ggplot(my_diamonds, aes(price, fill = cut)) + 
    geom_density(alpha = .3)

The variables color and clarity are both categorical variables, and their distribution is generally displayed by bar plots.

  1. Display a stacked, a dodged, and a filled bar plot of these variables in a 1 x 3 plot array. Use the plot_layout() function to display the legend and axes labels only once.
ggplot(my_diamonds, aes(color, fill = clarity)) + 
    geom_bar() +
  
ggplot(my_diamonds, aes(color, fill = clarity)) + 
    geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
  
ggplot(my_diamonds, aes(color, fill = clarity)) + 
    geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  
  plot_layout(guides = "collect", axes = "collect")

  1. Now display the joint distribution of these two variables with geom_count().
ggplot(my_diamonds, aes(color, clarity)) + 
    geom_count()

Three variables

The most common plot is that with two numeric variables and one categorical variable, with the levels of the categorical variable displayed with different shapes or colors.

  1. Display two scatter plots of price and carat in a 1 x 2 plot array, once with different sizes for price, and once with different shapes for cut. Make the points transparent by setting alpha to an appropriate value.
ggplot(my_diamonds, aes(price, carat, size = price)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .1) +

ggplot(my_diamonds, aes(price, carat, col = cut)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .5)

  1. The plot with different colors for cut is not very clear. Reproduce the plot by adding a facet_wrap() layer, and add price for the size of the points.
ggplot(my_diamonds, aes(price, carat, col = cut)) +
  geom_point(aes(size = price), alpha = .5) +
  facet_wrap(vars(cut))

  1. Display the previous plot with a different theme (choose one that you think looks nice).
ggplot(my_diamonds, aes(price, carat, col = cut)) +
  geom_point(aes(size = price), alpha = .5) +
  facet_wrap(vars(cut)) +
  theme_classic()

Advanced

  1. Display a graphical representation of the variables price, carat, depth, cut and color.
ggplot(my_diamonds, aes(price, carat, col = depth)) +
  geom_point(aes(size = color), alpha = .5) +
  facet_wrap(vars(cut)) +
  theme_minimal()
